node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Today in American History on January 28, 2021. May be an image of text that says '#OnThisDay in 1986 the Space Shuttle #Challenger exploded just 73 seconds into flight.'.

node.text:
It is estimated that roughly 20% of the American population watched the events unfold on live television. This was partly due to the presence of payload specialist Christa McAuliffe, who would have been the first teacher/private citizen in space. The disaster lead to the deaths of all seven crew members. 
After the disaster, President Ronald Reagan appointed a special commission called the Rogers Commission to thoroughly investigate the incident. The resulting investigation revealed that NASA's organizational culture and decision-making processes were key contributing factors in the disaster. Managers at NASA were aware of potentially catastrophic flaws in the design of some components and failed to properly address them. (Photo: Bruce Weaver/AP)
.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Today in American History on December 25, 2020. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'Bae: Come over Me: can't, the river's frozen Bae: My parents aren't home Me:'.

node.text: On #ChristmasDay in 1776, General George Washington crossed the cold and icy Delaware River with over 5,000 troops hoping to surprise the Hessian forces at Trenton. Only 2,400 troops successfully made it to the meeting point at the appropriate time but Washington's men were able to overcome the groggy Hessians without them. It wasn't a major win from a strategic standpoint but the victory was huge for the American colonists in terms of boosting morale. Washington Crossing the Delaware (1851), Emanuel Leutze (a depiction laden with historical inaccuracies). #merrychristmas #lol #haha #meme #memes #funny
